<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-label">01 — About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">The refrigerator call is the one you don't want to ignore.</h2>
        <p>Refrigerators are the one appliance that doesn't get a day off. When something goes wrong — the fridge runs but won't cool, the ice maker stops, water pools on the floor — food is at risk within hours. That's the reality of this repair in Los Angeles, where the ambient heat doesn't help.</p>
        <p>Our technicians run refrigerator calls across LA daily. West Hollywood high-rises, Beverly Hills estates with Sub-Zeros in the butler's pantry, Silver Lake rentals with basic Samsung units — we've seen the full range. Most refrigerators have the same failure modes regardless of price point: evaporator fan motors, condenser coils clogged with LA's omnipresent dust, defrost system failures, compressor issues. Our guys know exactly what they're walking into.</p>
        <p>We carry parts for the brands we see most often. That means the majority of refrigerator repairs get done on the first visit — not "we'll need to order that part and come back Thursday."</p>

        <div class="tip-box">
          <div class="tip-label">🌡 Los Angeles Climate Note</div>
          <p>In Southern California's warm, dry climate, refrigerator condenser coils accumulate dust and pet hair faster than in cooler regions. A fridge that was cooling fine last winter might struggle this summer — not because anything broke, but because the coils are overdue for cleaning. We include a coil inspection with every refrigerator service call.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="sticky-cta">
        <div class="cta-label">Same Day Refrigerator Repair</div>
        <a href={`tel:${phoneRaw}`} class="cta-phone">{phone}</a>
        <a href={`tel:${phoneRaw}`} class="btn-cta">Call Now — We Pick Up</a>
        <a href="/book" class="btn-cta" style="background:#222; margin-top: -4px;">Book Online</a>
        <div class="cta-sub">Mon–Fri 7am–9pm · Sat 8am–7pm · Sun 9am–5pm</div>
        <hr class="cta-divider" />
        <ul class="cta-detail">
          <li>$89 diagnostic fee — applied to repair</li>
          <li>90-day warranty on parts &amp; labor</li>
          <li>OEM parts for all major brands</li>
          <li>Written estimate before we start</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ============================================================
  04 PROBLEMS WE FIX
============================================================ -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — Common Issues</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians are called for most often</h2>
    <p class="lead">Every repair starts with a proper diagnosis. We don't replace parts on a guess — our technicians identify the root cause first, then give you a written quote.</p>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Refrigerator Not Cooling</h3>
        <p>The most common call we get. Could be condenser coils, evaporator fan failure, a sealed system problem, or a failing thermostat. Our technicians carry diagnostic tools to identify which one — not just the cheapest fix.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Ice Maker Not Working</h3>
        <p>Whether it stopped making ice entirely or is making too little — ice maker issues range from a blocked water line to a failed module to a freezer temperature problem. We find the actual cause.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Noisy Refrigerator</h3>
        <p>Buzzing from the back usually means condenser fan motor. Clicking from inside points to the evaporator fan or defrost timer. Grinding or knocking at the bottom is the compressor — that one warrants urgency.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Water Leaking or Pooling</h3>
        <p>Clogged defrost drain is the most frequent cause — water backs up and pools under the crisper drawers or on the floor. Also: cracked door gaskets, failed water inlet valve, or a split water line to the ice maker.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Frost Buildup / Not Defrosting</h3>
        <p>Excessive frost in the freezer means the automatic defrost system isn't running correctly. Usually the defrost heater, defrost thermostat, or defrost timer. Left alone, it blocks the evaporator coils and eventually stops cooling.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Compressor Failure</h3>
        <p>A compressor that's clicking on and off without cooling, or not running at all, is a serious repair. We evaluate whether the compressor is worth replacing given the age and brand of the unit — and we're straight with you about it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Seal Problems</h3>
        <p>A worn or torn door gasket lets warm air in constantly, forcing the compressor to run almost non-stop. The refrigerator runs warm, your electricity bill climbs, and the compressor wears out early. A seal replacement is one of the better investments on an otherwise solid unit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Error Codes / Display Issues</h3>
        <p>Modern refrigerators display error codes that point toward specific failures. Our technicians are current on the diagnostic codes for Samsung, LG, Thermador, Sub-Zero and other brands — these codes tell the story accurately when you know how to read them.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

